TY  - JOUR
T1  - Intermediary Capital and the Credit Market
AU  - Harris, Milton
AU  - Opp, Christian C.
AU  - Opp, Marcus M.
Y1  - 2024/03/29
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2025/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2020.01536
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2020.01536
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 162
EP  - 183
VL  - 71
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We propose a tractable framework to examine the role of intermediary capital in the allocation and pricing of credit. In our model, regulated financial intermediaries compete with unregulated investors, targeting distributions of heterogeneous borrowers. We derive a sufficient statistic that characterizes intermediaries? cross-sectional lending decisions and provide a novel intermediary asset pricing equation that accounts for the endogenous segmentation of marginal investors across securities. These formulae reveal the central role of intermediaries? shadow cost of capital in both credit allocation and pricing. Our results can concurrently rationalize a broad array of empirical facts documented in the context of credit markets.This paper was accepted by Tomasz Piskorski, finance.Funding: This work was supported by Marcus och Amalia Wallenbergs minnesfond [Grant 2021.0122].
AB  - We propose a tractable framework to examine the role of intermediary capital in the allocation and pricing of credit. In our model, regulated financial intermediaries compete with unregulated investors, targeting distributions of heterogeneous borrowers. We derive a sufficient statistic that characterizes intermediaries? cross-sectional lending decisions and provide a novel intermediary asset pricing equation that accounts for the endogenous segmentation of marginal investors across securities. These formulae reveal the central role of intermediaries? shadow cost of capital in both credit allocation and pricing. Our results can concurrently rationalize a broad array of empirical facts documented in the context of credit markets.This paper was accepted by Tomasz Piskorski, finance.Funding: This work was supported by Marcus och Amalia Wallenbergs minnesfond [Grant 2021.0122].
